Things of a civil Nature, common to Men, 〈◊〉
• ell as Chriſtians, to civil A •••• , as well as Religious (as Love feaſts, Kiſs of Charity) may be done without Divine appointment;
All our Anti-Ceremonial Men with one conſeut grant to all the world, the natural ſigns of Devotion, as the lifting up the Eyes and Hands to Heaven, bowing the Knee before God, if not injoyned (tho they are ſo) might be uſed. Alſo civil ſigns of Subjection, as Eleazers laying his hand under Abrahams Thigh, things done by Divine Inſtiuſt, things extorted by neceſſity and extraordinary Providences are no precedent to us, (as Anointing with Oil, which was pro tempore as was the miracle annexed to it,) theſe things are affirmed by Ames, and others; (I pray by the way, give over boaſting, Hooker was never anſwer'd till Dr. Ames's Freſh Suit be ſo.) Had it been the mind of God to teach his Church by Ceremonies, would not he himſelf have appointed them, as once he did? What place may not, or cannot the Croſs be uſed in? Did Dr Stillingfleet well anſwer Mr. Stillingfleet's Irenirum, or the excellent Preface thereto, I ſuppoſe, you do remember? The Church's power to appoint Ceremonies, was not in the old 39 Articles. How came they in the new ones? 147 Pſalm, To make the power of the Church to bind the conſciences of of Men, was put in the Contents by ſome Innovators, to make it canonical, ſeeing they could not find it in the Text.
